# Workflow Patterns Reference

Proven architectural patterns for building n8n workflows.

---

## The 5 Core Patterns

### 1. Webhook Processing (Most Common)

```
Webhook → [Validate] → [Transform] → [Action] → [Response/Notify]
```
- Receive HTTP requests from external systems <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Use cases: form submissions, payment webhooks, chat commands, GitHub webhooks <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **CRITICAL**: Data under `$json.body`, NOT `$json` directly <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Response modes: `onReceived` (immediate 200, background processing) vs `lastNode` (custom response via Webhook Response node) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

### 2. HTTP API Integration

```
Trigger → HTTP Request → [Transform] → [Action] → [Error Handler]
```
- Fetch from REST APIs, transform, store/use <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Use cases: data fetching, API-to-API sync, enrichment, monitoring <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Auth methods: None, Bearer Token, API Key, Basic Auth, OAuth2 <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Always use credentials system (never hardcode) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

### 3. Database Operations

```
Trigger → [Query/Read] → [Transform] → [Write/Update] → [Verify]
```
- Read/write/sync database data <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Use cases: ETL, data sync, cleanup, backup, real-time updates <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **CRITICAL**: Always use parameterized queries (`$1`, `?`) — never string concatenation <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Supported: Postgres, MySQL, MongoDB, MSSQL, SQLite, Redis <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

### 4. AI Agent Workflow

```
Trigger → AI Agent (Model + Tools + Memory) → [Process] → Output
```
- AI agents with tool access, memory, and reasoning <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Use cases: chatbots, document Q&A, data analysis, automation agents <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- See [AI Agent section](#ai-agent-workflows) below <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

### 5. Scheduled Tasks

```
Schedule → [Fetch Data] → [Process] → [Deliver] → [Log/Notify]
```
- Recurring automation workflows <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Use cases: reports, syncs, monitoring, cleanup, content publishing <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

---

## Pattern Selection Guide

| Need | Pattern | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| Receive events from external systems | Webhook | Stripe payment → update DB |
| Fetch data from APIs | HTTP API | GitHub issues → Jira tickets |
| Database read/write/sync | Database | Postgres → MySQL sync |
| AI with tool access | AI Agent | Chat with DB + API access |
| Recurring automation | Scheduled | Daily report → email team |

---

## Data Flow Patterns

| Flow | Structure | When |
|------|-----------|------|
| Linear | `Trigger → Transform → Action → End` | Simple single-path |
| Branching | `Trigger → IF → [True] / [False]` | Conditional actions |
| Parallel | `Trigger → [Branch 1] + [Branch 2] → Merge` | Independent ops |
| Loop | `Trigger → Split In Batches → Process → Loop` | Large datasets |
| Error Handler | `Main Flow + Error Trigger → Handler` | Separate error handling |

---

## Common Components

**Triggers**: Webhook (instant), Schedule (periodic), Manual (testing), Polling (intervals)

**Data Sources**: HTTP Request (APIs), Database nodes, Service nodes (Slack, Sheets), Code

**Transformation**: Set (field mapping), Code (complex logic), IF/Switch (routing), Merge (combine streams)

**Outputs**: HTTP Request (APIs), Database (write), Communication (email, Slack), Storage (files, cloud)

**Error Handling**: Error Trigger (catch errors), IF (check conditions), Stop and Error (explicit fail), continueOnFail (per-node)

---

## AI Agent Workflows

### 8 AI Connection Types

| Type | Purpose | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| `ai_languageModel` | The LLM | OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini |
| `ai_tool` | Functions agent can call | HTTP Request, DB, Code |
| `ai_memory` | Conversation context | Buffer, Window Buffer, Summary |
| `ai_outputParser` | Parse structured outputs | JSON, XML parsers |
| `ai_embedding` | Vector embeddings | OpenAI Embeddings |
| `ai_vectorStore` | Vector database | Pinecone, Qdrant |
| `ai_document` | Document loaders | File, URL loaders |
| `ai_textSplitter` | Text chunking | Character, Token splitter |

### Making ANY Node a Tool

Connect any n8n node to AI Agent via `ai_tool` port (NOT main port):

```javascript
{
  name: "search_github_issues",
  description: "Search GitHub issues by keyword. Returns issue titles and URLs.",
  // + normal HTTP Request config
}
```

**Tool descriptions matter**: AI uses them to decide WHEN to call tools. Be specific, not vague.

### Agent Types

| Type | Best For | When |
|------|----------|------|
| Conversational Agent | General chat, support | Most common |
| OpenAI Functions Agent | Tool-heavy workflows | Multiple tools, structured output |
| ReAct Agent | Step-by-step reasoning | Complex multi-step tasks |

### Memory Types

| Type | Behavior | Recommendation |
|------|----------|----------------|
| Buffer Memory | Store all messages | Short conversations |
| Window Buffer Memory | Store last N messages | **Recommended** for most cases |
| Summary Memory | Summarize old messages | Long conversations |

```javascript
// Window Buffer Memory config
{
  sessionKey: "={{$json.body.session_id}}",
  contextWindowLength: 10
}
```

### AI Agent Prompt Structure

```
You are a [ROLE].

You can:
- [CAPABILITY 1] <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- [CAPABILITY 2] <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

Guidelines:
- [GUIDELINE 1] <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- [GUIDELINE 2] <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

Format:
- [OUTPUT FORMAT] <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
```

### AI Security

- **Read-only DB access** for tools (`GRANT SELECT` only) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Validate tool inputs** (block DROP, DELETE, UPDATE in SQL) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Sanitize user input** (trim, length limit) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Rate limiting** on webhooks <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Monitor tool usage** for abuse <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

### Common AI Gotchas

| Wrong | Correct |
|-------|---------|
| Tools connected to main port | Connect via `ai_tool` port |
| Vague tool description: "Get data" | Specific: "Query customer orders by email" |
| No memory for conversations | Add Window Buffer Memory via `ai_memory` |
| Full DB access for AI tools | Read-only DB user |
| Unbounded tool responses | `LIMIT 10` in queries |

---

## Webhook Configuration

### Data Structure

```json
{
  "headers": {"content-type": "...", "x-api-key": "..."},
  "params": {"id": "123"},           // URL params: /webhook/:id
  "query": {"token": "abc"},         // Query: ?token=abc
  "body": { /* YOUR DATA IS HERE */ }
}
```

### Authentication

- **Query token**: `{{$json.query.token}}` (simple) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Header auth**: `{{$json.headers['x-api-key']}}` (better) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Signature verification**: HMAC with secret (best — for Stripe, GitHub) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

---

## Schedule Configuration

### Modes

```javascript
// Interval: every 15 min
{ mode: "interval", interval: 15, unit: "minutes" }

// Days & Hours: weekdays at 9 AM
{ mode: "daysAndHours", days: ["monday","tuesday","wednesday","thursday","friday"], hour: 9 }

// Cron: complex schedules
{ mode: "cron", expression: "0 9 * * 1-5" }  // Weekdays 9 AM
```

### Cron Quick Reference

```
minute hour day month weekday
0 9 * * 1-5      Weekdays 9 AM
*/15 * * * *      Every 15 min
0 0 1 * *         First day of month midnight
0 */6 * * *       Every 6 hours
```

### Key Practices

- **Set workflow timezone** explicitly in settings <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Prevent overlaps**: use Redis lock for long-running tasks <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Early exit**: check if data exists before heavy processing <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Batch processing**: `Split In Batches` for large datasets <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

---

## HTTP API Configuration

### Authentication Methods

| Method | Config |
|--------|--------|
| None | `authentication: "none"` |
| Bearer Token | `nodeCredentialType: "httpHeaderAuth"` |
| API Key | Header or query parameter |
| Basic Auth | `nodeCredentialType: "httpBasicAuth"` |
| OAuth2 | `nodeCredentialType: "oAuth2Api"` |

### Pagination Patterns

- **Offset-based**: increment page, check `has_more` <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Cursor-based**: use `next_cursor` from response <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Link header**: parse `rel="next"` URL <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

### Rate Limiting

- **Wait between requests**: `Split In Batches` + `Wait` node <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Exponential backoff**: 1s → 2s → 4s retry delays <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- **Respect headers**: check `x-ratelimit-remaining` <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

---

## Database Best Practices

### Parameterized Queries (CRITICAL)

```javascript
// SAFE
{ query: "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1", parameters: ["={{$json.id}}"] }

// DANGEROUS (SQL injection)
{ query: "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '={{$json.id}}'" }
```

### Batch Processing

```
Query (LIMIT 10000) → Split In Batches (100) → Process → Loop
```

### Transactions

```
BEGIN → Operations (continueOnFail) → COMMIT or ROLLBACK
```

### Performance

- Add database indexes for query columns <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Always use `LIMIT` on SELECT <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Use cursor-based pagination for large tables (`WHERE id > $1 ORDER BY id LIMIT 1000`) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Batch writes (insert arrays, not individual rows) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

---

## Error Handling Patterns

### 1. Error Trigger Workflow

```
Main: Trigger → Process → Output
Error: Error Trigger → Log → Slack Alert
```

### 2. Retry with Backoff

```
HTTP Request (continueOnFail) → IF (error) → Wait → Retry → IF (still error) → Alert
```

### 3. [[Validation]] Early Exit

```
Webhook → IF (validate) → [True: Process] / [False: 400 Error Response]
```

### 4. Partial Failure Handling

```
Split In Batches → Process (continueOnFail) → Code (track successes/failures) → Report
```

---

## Quick Start Examples

### Webhook → Slack

```
1. Webhook (POST, path: "form-submit")
2. Set (map fields from $json.body)
3. Slack (post to #notifications)
```

### Scheduled Report

```
1. Schedule (daily 9 AM)
2. HTTP Request (fetch analytics)
3. Code (aggregate data)
4. Email (formatted report)
5. Error Trigger → Slack (notify on failure)
```

### AI Assistant

```
1. Webhook (receive chat message)
2. AI Agent
   ├─ OpenAI Chat Model (ai_languageModel)
   ├─ HTTP Request Tool (ai_tool)
   ├─ Postgres Tool (ai_tool, read-only)
   └─ Window Buffer Memory (ai_memory)
3. Webhook Response (send AI reply)
```

### Database Sync

```
1. Schedule (every 15 min)
2. Postgres (SELECT WHERE updated_at > last_sync)
3. IF (records exist)
4. MySQL (INSERT/UPDATE)
5. Postgres (UPDATE sync_log)
```

---

## Workflow Creation Checklist

**Planning**: Identify pattern → List nodes ([[mcp-tools|search_nodes]]) → Plan data flow → Plan error handling

**Implementation**: Create with trigger → Add data sources → Configure auth → Add transformation → Add outputs → Add error handling

**[[Validation]]**: [[mcp-tools|validate_node]] each node → validate_workflow → Test with sample data → Handle edge cases

**Deployment**: Review settings → Activate (`activateWorkflow` operation) → Monitor first executions

## Instagram Publishing (Meta Graph API)

### Single Image Post

```
Webhook → POST /{ig}/media (image_url + caption) → Wait 10s → POST /{ig}/media_publish
```

```javascript
// Step 1: Create media container
POST https://graph.facebook.com/v18.0/{ig_user_id}/media
{ "image_url": "https://...", "caption": "...", "access_token": "..." }
// → { "id": "container_id" }

// Step 2: Publish
POST https://graph.facebook.com/v18.0/{ig_user_id}/media_publish
{ "creation_id": "container_id", "access_token": "..." }
```

### Carousel Post

```
POST /{ig}/media (is_carousel_item=true) × N
→ POST /{ig}/media (CAROUSEL, children=[...])
→ POST /{ig}/media_publish
```

**Active workflow**: `gRjdWA4KKjRH2kCM` (single image only — carousel TODO)

**Note**: `image_url` must be a public URL. Upload to `wp-content/uploads/smm/` via SCP first if needed.

## YouTube / n8n Video Processing Patterns

### YouTube Access from VPS

All public Invidious instances unsuitable for VPS — 20-30s timeout overhead before failure (inv.nadeko.net timeout, privacyredirect.com 404, fdn.fr DNS unresolved). **Only reliable method:** cookies-based authentication via yt-dlp.

### Telegram Local Bot-API: Filesystem Paths vs HTTP URLs

Local `telegram-bot-api` returns absolute filesystem paths, not HTTP URLs.

**Fix:** Detect path format — if absolute filesystem path, read directly from disk instead of attempting HTTP fetch.

### Binary Transfer: Pass URLs Not Payloads

n8n binary transfer via Download File → Transcribe File node chain is unreliable.

**Fix:** Pass `telegram_url` directly to downstream video-service instead of binary payload. General rule: pass URLs between services instead of binary payloads via HTTP when possible.

### [[Claude]] + Telegram Delivery

- Always **disable `parse_mode`** when [[Claude]] controls text content (---, ##, ** break Telegram renderer) <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Strip code fences in Extract Note node: `.replace(/\`\`\`[\w]*\n|\`\`\`/g, '')` <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

## n8n Workflow Debugging Quick Reference

```
1. Check execution logs:   mcp__n8n-mcp__n8n_executions
2. Inspect workflow:       mcp__n8n-mcp__n8n_get_workflow  (before changes)
3. Inline fixes:           mcp__n8n-mcp__n8n_update_partial_workflow
4. Validate after:         mcp__n8n-mcp__n8n_get_workflow
```

## API Error Handling Patterns (General)

- Validate API response objects before calling string methods — wrap in `try-catch` with `typeof` checks <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Log error type separately (`RequestBlocked` / `NoTranscript` / `ParseError`) for operational debugging <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- Test error paths explicitly (no captions, blocked IP, missing data) — not just happy path <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->
- For cloud-blocked services, pivot to user-provided files instead of fighting IP bans <!-- decay:2026-03-25 tier:cold rel:0.4 -->

## Large Media File Pipeline Pattern

1. Detect source protocol/format
2. Normalize to intermediate format (mp3/jpg)
3. Implement streaming/chunking for processing
4. Aggregate results before final delivery

Always check if local/self-hosted versions of APIs exist (e.g., telegram-bot-api, llm inference) — often remove size limits entirely and reduce latency.

## Vision + Transcription Pipeline

Extract frames → describe visually → combine with speech recognition → richer context for downstream LLM. Captures content that audio-only misses.

